    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Rapidly Decaying Functions are Schwartz Functions
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Hernandez%2C+F">Felipe Hernandez</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Riedel%2C+C+J">C. Jess Riedel</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.14183v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        We show that if the Wigner function of a (possibly mixed) quantum state decays toward infinity faster than any polynomial in the phase space variables $x$ and $p$, then so do all of its derivatives, i.e., it is a Schwartz function on phase space. This is equivalent to the condition that the Husimi function is a Schwartz function, that the quantum state is a Schwartz operator in the sense of Keyl e&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.14183v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.14183v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.14183v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        We show that if the Wigner function of a (possibly mixed) quantum state decays toward infinity faster than any polynomial in the phase space variables $x$ and $p$, then so do all of its derivatives, i.e., it is a Schwartz function on phase space. This is equivalent to the condition that the Husimi function is a Schwartz function, that the quantum state is a Schwartz operator in the sense of Keyl et al., and, in the case of a pure state, that the wavefunction is a Schwartz function on configuration space. We discuss the interpretation of this constraint on Wigner functions and provide explicit bounds on Schwartz seminorms.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.14183v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.14183v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

