    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Constraint optimization and $\mathcal{SU}(N)$ quantum control landscapes
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Birtea%2C+P">Petre Birtea</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Casu%2C+I">Ioan Casu</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Comanescu%2C+D">Dan Comanescu</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.11132v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        We develop the embedded gradient vector field method, introduced in [8] and [9], for the case of the special unitary group $\mathcal{SU}(N)$ regarded as a constraint submanifold of the unitary group $\mathcal{U}(N)$. The optimization problem associated to the trace fidelity cost function defined on $\mathcal{SU}(N)$ that appears in the context of $\mathcal{SU}(N)$ quantum control landscapes is com&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.11132v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.11132v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.11132v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        We develop the embedded gradient vector field method, introduced in [8] and [9], for the case of the special unitary group $\mathcal{SU}(N)$ regarded as a constraint submanifold of the unitary group $\mathcal{U}(N)$. The optimization problem associated to the trace fidelity cost function defined on $\mathcal{SU}(N)$ that appears in the context of $\mathcal{SU}(N)$ quantum control landscapes is completely solved using the embedded gradient vector field method. We prove that for $N\geq 5$, the landscape is not $\mathcal{SU}(N)$-trap free, there are always kinematic local extrema that are not global extrema.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.11132v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.11132v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 20 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    

    
